e operators, '''TrueMove H''', which is second only to [[Advanced Info Service|AIS]] having surpassed [[Dtac]] in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.developingtelecoms.com/business/operator-news/7040-true-takes-second-place-in-thai-market-as-dtac-profits-slump.html|title=True takes second place in Thai market as Dtac profits slump|last=Barton|first=James|website=Developing Telecoms|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> As of August 2014, True, along with True Telecommunications Growth Infrastructure Fund, had a combined market capitalization of US$10 billion.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} TrueMove is also a partner of [[Vodafone Group]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vodafone and Conexus Mobile Alliance Form Strategic Partnership |url=https://www.vodafone.com/content/index/media/vodafone-group-releases/2011/conexus_partnership.html |website=www.vodafone.com |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrue is a subsidiary of [[Charoen Pokphand Group]], which holds 50.21 percent of True's shares as of March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.truecorp.co.th/shareholders.html|title=Investor Relations|last=Shareinvestor|website=True|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref> It operates fixed-line (as a concessionaire of TOT), [[wireless]], [[cable TV]], [[IPTV]] and [[broadband]] services.\n\n==History==\nTrue Corporation was established on 13 November 1990 as '''TelecomAsia'''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/thailand/bangkok-post/20150330/282574491577094|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> The company had partnership with [[Verizon]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The company was listed on the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]] on {{Start date|1993|12|22}}.<ref name=\"SETCompanyProfile\">{{cite web|title=TRUE Company Profile|url=http://www.set.or.th/set/companyprofile.do?Bahtsymbol=TRUE|website=Stock Exchange of Thailand|accessdate=3 July 2010}}</ref> In 2001, TelecomAsia set up a mobile phone subsidiary with [[Orange S.A.|Orange SA]]. Orange sold off its stake in 2003 but the Orange brand was used until 2006.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FGI/is_4_15/ai_n6040967 | work=Telecom Asia | title=TA Orange's strategic partner Orange SA sells off 39% of its 49% stake in the Thai mobile operator to TelecomAsia for a nominal one Baht | date=2004-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn an effort to converge TelecomAsia's telecommunication business into a single brand, the company renamed itself to True Corporation in 2004,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.th/books?id=dPgGGhvgfikC&pg=PA336&lpg=PA336&dq=2004+TRUe+corporation+telecomasia&source=bl&ots=cTEdP5f0Bj&sig=Byje3UIm7DLGZGAizorADXs7ldE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjhiPqepYvZAhWEsY8KHT2-BhAQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=2004%20TRUe%20corporation%20telecomasia&f=false|title=Southeast Asia's Chinese Businesses in an Era of Globalization: Coping with the Rise of China|last=Suryadinata|first=Leo|date=2006|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|isbn=9789812304018|language=en}}</ref> and streamlined its operations with subsidiaries Asia Infonet (renamed True Internet{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}) and Orange (renamed True Move in 2006<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegeography.com/products/commsupdate/articles/2006/02/08/orange-reaches-use-by-date-true-corps-mobile-unit-renamed-true-move/|title=Orange reaches use-by date: True Corp's mobile unit renamed True Move|website=TeleGeography|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref>).\n\nIn 2005, True took a higher stake in [[United Broadcasting Corporation|UBC]], Thailand's largest [[cable television]] provider that time{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}, and renamed the company to UBC-True.<ref>Amnatcharoenrit, Bamrung and Tortermvasana, Komsan (8 November 2005). [http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=33025 \"True Corp set to take over UBC\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080311233416/http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/article.asp?parentid=33025 |date=2008-03-11}}, ''Bangkok Post'' (retrieved 18 July 2006 until 18 August 2015 via AsiaMedia.com).</ref> On 24 January 2007 UBC-True was renamed [[TrueVisions]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nOn 8 May 2013, TrueMove H became Thailand's first mobile operator to provide 4G LTE commercial service on the 2100&nbsp;MHz bandwidth.<ref name=\"thaipr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thaipr.net/communication/476291|title=True Move H \u2013 The First To Offer 4G LTE Service On 2100 MHz In Thailand While Reinforcing Its Leadership As The Largest 3G Operator,|work=thaipr.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 2014, it was announced that [[China Mobile]] agreed to purchase 18 percent of its shares for US$881 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=China Mobile to buy $881mln stake in Thai billionaire's True Corp|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/09/us-true-corporation-chinamobile-idUSKBN0EK0QA20140609|date=June 9, 2014|author=Jittapong, Khettiya|accessdate=11 June 2014| agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=China Mobile to buy into True |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/414439/china-mobile-to-buy-into-true|date=June 10, 2014|author1=Phoosuphanusorn, Srisamorn  |author2=Leesa-nguansuk, Suchit |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=June 11, 2014|work=Bangkok Post}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 November 2014, Truemove H announced that it allocated 10 billion baht to expand its 4G LTE network in Thailand to cover 80 percent of the country's population.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mobileasia.net/?p=10252|title=True announced high-speed Internet in Bangkok with all-fiber network in 2 years|work=Mobileasia}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015 [[Suphachai Chearavanont]], True's President and CEO, was presented with the \"2015 [[Frost & Sullivan]] Asia Pacific Telecom CEO of the Year\" award in Singapore for his leadership and achievements in developing the telecommunications industry in the Asia Pacific region.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} In the same month, Chearavanont was elected president of The Telecommunications Association of Thailand.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\n==Subsidiaries==\nTrue Corporation includes the following subsidiaries:<ref>{{cite web|title=Annual Report 2014|url=http://true.listedcompany.com/misc/AR/ar2014-en.html}}</ref>\n* [[TrueMove H|TrueMobile]] (Mobile telecommunication)\n** True Move Co., Ltd.\n** Real Move Co., Ltd.\n** True Move H Universal Communication Co., Ltd.\n** BFKT (Thailand) Limited\n* TrueOnline (Broadband/fixed line business)\n** Asia Infonet Co., Ltd.\n** Asia Wireless Communication Co., Ltd.\n** KSC Commercial Internet Co., Ltd.\n** MKSC World Dot Com Co., Ltd.\n** True International Communication Co., Ltd.\n** True International Gateway Co., Ltd.\n** True Internet Co., Ltd.\n** True Public Communication Co., Ltd.\n** True Universal Convergence Co., Ltd.\n* [[TrueVisions]] (Pay TV business)\n** BEC-TERO True Visions Co., Ltd.\n** Click TV Co., Ltd.\n** Satellite Service Co., Ltd.\n** Thai News Network (TNN) Co., Ltd.\n** True4U Station Co., Ltd.\n** [[TrueVisions|True Visions Plc.]]\n** True Visions Cable Plc.\n** True Visions Group Co., Ltd.\n** True Vistas Co., Ltd.\n* Content, lifestyle and other businesses:\n** AP&J Production Co., Ltd.\n** Cineplex Co., Ltd.\n** True CJ Creations (joint venture with South Korea's [[CJ ENM]])\n** Panther Entertainment Co., Ltd.\n** SM True (joint venture with South Korea's [[S.M. Entertainment]])<ref>{{cite web|title=True Group, in Collaboration with S.M. Entertainment from South Korea, Establishes a Joint-Venture \"SM True Co., Ltd.\"To Bring A New Era of Entertainment to Thailand|url=http://www2.truecorp.co.th/en/pc_press_detail.aspx?id=1443|work=True Corporation|accessdate=16 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S.M. Entertainment establishes joint venture company with Thailand\u2019s True Visions Group, \u2018SM True\u2019|url=http://www.allkpop.com/2011/08/sm-entertainment-establishes-joint-venture-company-with-thailands