{"title_page": "Health Research Authority", "text_new": "[[File:Health Research Authority logo.svg|thumb|Health Research Authority logo]]\nThe '''Health Research Authority''' ('''HRA''') is an executive [[non-departmental public body]] of the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"HRAweb\" >{{cite web | url=http://www.hra.nhs.uk/ | title=Health Research Authority | accessdate= 18 April 2013}}</ref> The HRA exists to provide a unified national system for the governance of health research. The current chair of the HRA is Professor Sir [[Terence Stephenson]], who succeeded Sir [[Jonathan Montgomery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hra.nhs.uk/about-the-hra/board | title= Health Research Authority |accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe formation of the HRA came as a result of reorganisation of the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS) in [[England]] outlined in the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]], and took on the functions of the National Research Ethics Service.<ref name=\"HRAweb\" /> Originally established as a [[Special Health Authority]] on 1 December 2011, it became a [[non-departmental public body]] on 1 January 2015 under the [[Care Act 2014]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official|https://www.hra.nhs.uk/}}\n\n{{Department of Health (United Kingdom)}}\n\n[[Category:2005 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British medical research]]\n[[Category:Department of Health and Social Care]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Health in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n[[Category:Non-departmental public bodies of the United Kingdom government]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Health Research Authority logo.svg|thumb|Health Research Authority logo]]\nThe '''Health Research Authority''' ('''HRA''') is an executive [[non-departmental public body]] of the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"HRAweb\" >{{cite web | url=http://www.hra.nhs.uk/ | title=Health Research Authority | accessdate= 18 April 2013}}</ref> The HRA exists to provide a unified national system for the governance of health research. The current chair of the HRA is Professor Sir Terence Stephenson, who succeeded Sir [[Jonathan Montgomery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hra.nhs.uk/about-the-hra/board | title= Health Research Authority |accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe formation of the HRA came as a result of reorganisation of the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] (NHS) in [[England]] outlined in the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]], and took on the functions of the National Research Ethics Service.<ref name=\"HRAweb\" /> Originally established as a [[Special Health Authority]] on 1 December 2011, it became a [[non-departmental public body]] on 1 January 2015 under the [[Care Act 2014]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official|https://www.hra.nhs.uk/}}\n\n{{Department of Health (United Kingdom)}}\n\n[[Category:2005 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British medical research]]\n[[Category:Department of Health and Social Care]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Health in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n[[Category:Non-departmental public bodies of the United Kingdom government]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n", "name_user": "Experienced hand", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to Sir Terrence Stephenson's Wikipedia page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_Research_Authority"}
{"title_page": "Tomb Raider (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Roar Uthaug}}\n{{about|the 2018 film starring Alicia Vikander|the 2001 film starring Angelina Jolie|Lara Croft: Tomb Raider}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tomb Raider\n| image          = Tomb Raider (2018 film).png\n| alt            = A close-up shot of a gritty-looking Lara Croft is seen with the film's title, her actress' name and company logos on the bottom.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roar Uthaug]]\n| producer       = [[Graham King]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Geneva Robertson-Dworet]]\n* Alastair Siddons\n}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Evan Daugherty\n* Geneva Robertson-Dworet\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Tomb Raider (2013 video game)|Tomb Raider]]''|[[Crystal Dynamics]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Alicia Vikander]]\n* [[Dominic West]]\n* [[Walton Goggins]]\n* [[Daniel Wu]]\n* [[Kristin Scott Thomas]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Junkie XL|Tom Holkenborg]]\n| cinematography = [[George Richmond (cinematographer)|George Richmond]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Stuart Baird]]\n* [[Michael Tronick]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]<ref name=\"insight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php|title=Film Releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315044131/https://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php|work=[[Variety Insight]]|publisher=Variety Media|accessdate=March 15, 2018|archivedate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]<ref name=\"insight\" /> \n* [[GK Films]]<ref name=\"insight\" />\n* [[Square Enix]]<ref name=\"insight\" />\n}}\n| distributor    = Warner Bros. Pictures<ref name=\"insight\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|3|2|[[Berlin]]|ref1=<ref name=\"prem1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvd-forum.at/news-details/69347-events-tomb-raider-das-war-die-exklusive-preview-mit-alicia-vikander |title=\"Tomb Raider\": Das war die exklusive Preview mit Alicia Vikander|date=March 3, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018|work=DVD-Forum.at |first=Daniel |last=Fabian |language=de}}</ref><ref name=\"prem2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylbLMuhrkW0|title=TOMB RAIDER - Premierenclip Deutsch HD German (2018)|work=Warner Bros. DE|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094038/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylbLMuhrkW0|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>|2018|3|14|United Kingdom|2018|3|16|United States}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/tomb-raider-film | title=TOMB RAIDER (12A) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=February 23, 2018 | accessdate=March 8, 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309182707/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/tomb-raider-film | archivedate=March 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=BFI>{{cite web|title=Tomb Raider (2018)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5aa1d2662fc38|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316030150/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5aa1d2662fc38|archive-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=BFI/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90\u2013106 million<ref name=\"opening\" />\n| gross          = $275 million<ref>{{cite web |author=MGM PR |title=Michael De Luca to Replace Jonathan Glickman at MGM |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/jonathan-glickman-mgm-bond-michael-de-luca-1203456176/ |website=Variety |publisher=Variety |accessdate=4 January 2020|date=2020-01-03 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Tomb Raider''''' is a 2018 [[Action film|action]] [[adventure film]] directed by [[Roar Uthaug]], with a screenplay by [[Geneva Robertson-Dworet]] and Alastair Siddons, from a story by [[Evan Daugherty]] and Robertson-Dworet. An [[United States|American]] and [[United Kingdom|British]] co-production, it is based on the [[Tomb Raider (2013 video game)|2013 video game of the same name]], with some elements of [[Rise of the Tomb Raider|its sequel]] by [[Crystal Dynamics]], and is a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of the ''[[Tomb Raider]]'' film series. The film stars [[Alicia Vikander]] as [[Lara Croft]], who embarks on a perilous journey to her father's last-known destination, hoping to solve the mystery of his disappearance. [[Dominic West]], [[Walton Goggins]], [[Daniel Wu]], and [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] appear in supporting roles.\n\n[[Principal photography]] lasted from January to June 2017, and took place at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, and in [[Cape Town]], South Africa. The first ''Tomb Raider'' film not to be distributed by [[Paramount Pictures]], it was released in the United Kingdom on March 14, 2018, and in the United States on March 16, 2018, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], in [[RealD 3D]], [[IMAX|IMAX 3D]], [[IMAX]] and [[4DX]].<ref name=\"4D\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kitag.com/en/movies/tomb-raider-4dx/|title='Tomb Raider' - 4DX|work=Kitag|date=March 1, 2018|accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> The film grossed over $275 million worldwide, outperforming both the 2001 film [[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider|of the same name]] and its 2003 [[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider \u2013 The Cradle of Life|sequel]].\n\n''Tomb Raider'' received mixed reviews from critics, with some describing the plot as paint \"by-the-numbers\", and others praising the action sequences, tone, grittiness and realistic take on the franchise. Vikander's performance and the characterization of Croft drew a polarized response; some described her as a \"capable, powerful, and unobjectified heroine\", while others called her bland, and a \"punching bag and onlooker.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=March 14, 2018 |title= 'Tomb Raider': What the Critics Are Saying |first= Katie |last= Kilkenny |work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher= [[Prometheus Global Media]] |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-review-roundup-1094464 |accessdate= October 24, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180314224426/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-review-roundup-1094464 |archive-date= March 14, 2018 }}</ref> A sequel is scheduled to be released in March 2021.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- As per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nFollowing the disappearance of her father, Lord Richard Croft, [[Lara Croft]] makes a living as a [[bike courier]]. When she is arrested after a bike accident involving a police car, Richard's business partner Ana Miller posts her bail. Lara has never claimed her inheritance for many years as she believes her father to still be alive, but Miller warns Lara that if she does not claim it, her father's country estate, Croft Manor, will be sold off. Lara reluctantly accepts and gains access to a secret chamber in her father's tomb. There she finds a pre-recorded video message from Richard detailing his research into [[Himiko]], the mythical Queen of [[Yamatai]] who was said to command the power over life and death. Richard warns Lara to destroy all of his research, but she ignores his warnings so that she can investigate further.\n\nLara travels to [[Hong Kong]] where she hires Lu Ren, captain of the ship ''Endurance'', to sail into the [[Devil's Sea]] and the island of Yamatai. The ship capsizes in a violent storm and Lara is washed ashore where she is knocked unconscious. She awakens only to encounter Mathias Vogel, the leader of an expedition to locate Himiko's tomb. The expedition has been funded by a shadowy organization called Trinity, which seeks to harness and weaponize Himiko's power. Vogel takes Lara prisoner, claiming that he killed her father and revealing that he intends to use Richard's research to continue his expedition. He adds Lara and Lu Ren to his slave force; eventually, the two of them try to escape, and Lara is the only one successful.\n\nAfter surviving rapids and narrowly avoiding going over a waterfall with the wreck of a wartime airplane, Lara is forced to kill a Trinity guard after nightfall. She follows a mysterious figure through the jungle, and discovers that the figure is her father, who stayed on the island to prevent Trinity from finding Himiko's tomb. After Lara convinces him that she is real and not a figment of his imagination, Richard treats her injuries. Despite his protests, Lara sets off the next morning to steal Vogel's satellite phone. Lara makes contact with Lu Ren, and he, along with the other slaves, stage a distraction that allows Lara to infiltrate the Trinity camp and take the phone. In the ensuing chaos, Lu Ren commandeers an assault rifle, provides cover for the escapees and guns down several Trinity soldiers, while Richard makes his way to Himiko's tomb and is captured by Vogel, who persuades Lara to open the tomb, something she has prepared for since she was a child. At that point, the entrance to the tomb self-destructs and falls away, thus enabling the party to enter that which has not been seen for at least two thousand years.\n\nThe party navigates a series of booby traps and locates Himiko's [[sarcophagus]]. When a Trinity soldier attempts to remove her corpse, he is infected by a highly infectious pathogen that reduces those infected to an aggressive zombie-like state. Lara realizes that Himiko was an asymptomatic carrier of the virus, who chose to entomb herself so that she could not infect others. Vogel concludes that he cannot remove Himiko's body and instead settles for detaching a finger, which he seals in a pouch. In the confusion, Lara and Richard overpower the remaining soldiers, although Vogel escapes and Richard becomes infected. Knowing there is no cure, Richard proposes destroying Himiko's tomb to prevent the disease from spreading across the world. Lara pursues Vogel as Richard sets off a bomb, killing himself and sealing the tomb. Lara confronts and kills Vogel by infecting him with the finger. She escapes the tomb as it collapses, regrouping with Lu Ren and the slaves; they commandeer a Trinity helicopter to escape Yamatai.\n\nLara returns to London, where she formally accepts her inheritance and inadvertently discovers that Trinity's [[front company]], Patna, is actually a [[subsidiary]] of Croft Holdings. She proceeds to investigate Trinity further and begins to suspect that Ana is one of their agents who manipulated her into accepting her inheritance; this was to have Lara sign over control of Croft Holdings' business operations to her when Richard stopped cooperating with Trinity. Having witnessed Trinity's ruthlessness firsthand, she prepares for her next adventure.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], Lara returns to Alan's pawn shop to buy weapons and decides to take two identical pistols.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Alicia Vikander]] as [[Lara Croft]]\n** Maisy De Freitas as 7-year-old Lara\n** [[Emily Carey]] as 14-year-old Lara\n* [[Dominic West]] as Lord Richard Croft, Lara's archaeologist father.\n* [[Walton Goggins]] as Mathias Vogel, a rival archaeologist of Richard Croft, and a member of Trinity, a shadowy organization.\n* [[Daniel Wu]] as Lu Ren, the ship captain who helps Lara to search for her father.\n* [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] as Ana Miller, an associate at Richard Croft's company, Croft Holdings.\n* [[Derek Jacobi]] as Mr. Yaffe, an associate at Croft Holdings.\n* [[Nick Frost]] as Alan, a pawn shop owner.\n* [[Jaime Winstone]] as Pamela, Alan's wife\n* [[Hannah John-Kamen]] as Sophie, Lara's friend\n\nAdditionally, [[Antonio Aakeel]] play Lara's friend Nitin. [[Duncan Airlie James]] plays Terry, a mixed martial arts club operator. [[Josef Altin]] portrays Lara's boss Bruce, Billy Postlethwaite and [[Roger Nsengiyumva]] appear as Bill and Rog, Lara's co-workers and opponents at the race, and [[Michael Obiora]] portrays Baxter, the Croft Holdings' receptionist.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[GK Films]] first acquired the rights to make the film in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/news/the-departed-the-town-producer-plans-tomb-raider-reboot-for-2013/|title='The Departed' & 'The Town' Producer Plans 'Tomb Raider' Reboot For 2013|publisher=The Film Stage|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094035/https://thefilmstage.com/news/the-departed-the-town-producer-plans-tomb-raider-reboot-for-2013/|archivedate=2018-03-18|date=2011-03-08}}</ref> Norwegian director [[Roar Uthaug]] came on board in November 2015,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Finds Director (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-reboot-finds-director-840824|accessdate=March 6, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310162405/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-reboot-finds-director-840824|archivedate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> and [[Alicia Vikander]] was cast as the new Lara Croft in April 2016.<ref name=\"VikanderCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Alicia Vikander to Star as Lara Croft in 'Tomb Raider'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alicia-vikander-star-as-lara-888593|accessdate=April 29, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=April 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828131755/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alicia-vikander-star-as-lara-888593|archivedate=August 28, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' had previously reported that [[Daisy Ridley]] was considered for the role,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Is 'Star Wars' Daisy Ridley Being Eyed As Lara Croft In 'Tomb Raider' Reboot?|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/daisy-ridley-lara-croft-tomb-raider-star-wars-force-awakens-1201717660/|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311114719/http://deadline.com/2016/03/daisy-ridley-lara-croft-tomb-raider-star-wars-force-awakens-1201717660/|archivedate=March 11, 2016}}</ref> though Ridley later stated in an interview that it was just \"the craziest rumor [she had] ever heard about [herself]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doUdRCrK80E|title=73 Questions With Daisy Ridley|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=January 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120134408/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doUdRCrK80E|archivedate=January 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Walton Goggins]] was announced to play the villain in December 2016,<ref name=\"GogginsCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Casts Walton Goggins as Villain Opposite Alicia Vikander (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-casts-walton-goggins-villain-alicia-vikander-1201886922/|accessdate=December 8, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209202819/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-casts-walton-goggins-villain-alicia-vikander-1201886922/|archivedate=December 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheridan|first1=Connor|title=Tomb Raider reboot movie is like Raiders of the Lost Ark according to bad guy actor Walton Goggins|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/tomb-raider-reboot-movie-is-like-raiders-of-the-lost-ark-according-to-bad-guy-actor-walton-goggins/|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|publisher=Future Publishing|accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217110901/http://www.gamesradar.com/tomb-raider-reboot-movie-is-like-raiders-of-the-lost-ark-according-to-bad-guy-actor-walton-goggins/|archivedate=December 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/tomb-raider-movie-walton-goggins-villain/|title='Tomb Raider': Walton Goggins on His \"Confused\", \"Angry\", and \"Desperate\" Villain|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|publisher=Future Media|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=December 27, 2016|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094033/http://collider.com/tomb-raider-movie-walton-goggins-villain/|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref> and much of the rest of the cast was revealed in early 2017.<ref name=WuCast>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/tomb-raider-reboot-daniel-wu-1201958245/|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Adds 'Into the Badlands' Star Daniel Wu (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094033/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/tomb-raider-reboot-daniel-wu-1201958245/|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestCast\">{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Dominic West Joins Alicia Vikander in 'Tomb Raider' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dominic-west-joins-alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-943069|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=January 27, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129194420/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dominic-west-joins-alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-943069|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Hannah John-Kamen Joins 'Tomb Raider' Cast; Andre Royo Steps Into Amazon's 'Beautiful Boy'|url=http://deadline.com/2017/04/hannah-john-kamen-tomb-raider-andre-royo-beauitful-boy-1202069567/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 13, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on January 23, 2017, in [[Cape Town]], South Africa, and wrapped on June 9, 2017, at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England.<ref name=\"Jan2017CS\">{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Spencer|title=New Tomb Raider Movie Filming Has Begun!|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/806047-production-officially-begins-on-the-new-tomb-raider-movie|accessdate=January 24, 2017|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=January 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125175132/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/806047-production-officially-begins-on-the-new-tomb-raider-movie|archivedate=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/tomb-raider-remake-production-start-date-2017/|title=Tomb Raider Reboot Begins Shooting in January 2017|date=December 22, 2016|accessdate=December 23, 2016|last=Scott|first=Ryan|work=[[MovieWeb]]|publisher=Watchr Media|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223034022/http://movieweb.com/tomb-raider-remake-production-start-date-2017/|archivedate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/tomb-raider-movie-head-production/|title=Tomb Raider Movie Is About To Head Into Production|date=December 22, 2016|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=We Got This Covered|last=Myles|first=Sarah|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223172433/http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/tomb-raider-movie-head-production/|archivedate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lesnick|first1=Silas|title=New Tomb Raider Movie Wraps Production|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/857033-new-tomb-raider-movie#/slide/1|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609194930/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/857033-new-tomb-raider-movie#/slide/1|archivedate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Wilton House]] near [[Salisbury]] in [[Wiltshire]] was the location for exterior shots for Croft Manor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1365519/locations?ref_=tt_ql_dt_5#filming_locations |title=Tomb Raider (2018): Filming & Production |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=April 6, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307191317/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1365519/locations?ref_=tt_ql_dt_5#filming_locations |archivedate=March 7, 2018 }}</ref> The waterfall sequence involving the plane was filmed at a waterpark at Lee Valley, outside of London, at a venue that had been built for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], and was combined with footage filmed in South Africa.<ref name=\"VFXVoice\">{{cite news|last1=Failes|first1=Ian|title=TOMB RAIDER: Transforming the Waterfall Scene with Frame-By-Frame VFX|url=http://vfxvoice.com/tomb-raider-transforming-the-waterfall-scene-with-frame-by-frame-vfx/|accessdate=April 10, 2018|work=VFX Voice|date=April 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411032905/http://vfxvoice.com/tomb-raider-transforming-the-waterfall-scene-with-frame-by-frame-vfx/|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main article|Tomb Raider (soundtrack)}}\nOn June 14, 2017, It was announced that [[Junkie XL]] signed on as the film's composer after being removed from ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Burlingame |first1=Russ |title=Junkie XL Issues Statement on Being \"Replaced\" On Justice League |url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2017/06/15/junkie-xl-issues-statement-on-being-replaced-on-justice-league/ |website=Comic Book |accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> The soundtrack was released digitally on March 9, 2018 by [[Sony Classical Records]], with the physical edition being released on March 16, 2018, followed by the vinyl on August 24, 2018.\n\n===Visual effects===\nThe visual effects are provided by [[Scanline VFX]] and Supervised by Nick Crew and Paul Linden with the help of [[Method Studios]], [[Rising Sun Pictures]], Mr. X, Soho VFX, [[ZERO VFX|Zero VFX]] and Factory VFX.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 1, 2019|title=TOMB RAIDER -The Art of VFXThe Art of VFX|url=https://www.artofvfx.com/tomb-raider/|website=www.artofvfx.com|date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Tomb Raider'' premiered on March 2, 2018, in [[Berlin]], Germany, at an exclusive preview with invited guests and [[cosplay]]ing fans.<ref name=\"prem1\" /><ref name=\"prem2\" /> It was released in the United States on March 16, 2018, by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Alicia Vikander's 'Tomb Raider' Gets 2018 Release Date|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-release-date-alicia-vikander-1201810114/|accessdate=July 10, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=July 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710042013/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-release-date-alicia-vikander-1201810114/|archivedate=July 10, 2016}}</ref>. The film received an [[IMAX 3D]] and a [[RealD 3D]] release.<ref>{{cite news|title=IMAX and Warner Bros. Extend Deal to Include 12 More Films|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/777749-imax-and-warner-bros-extend-deal-to-include-12-more-films#/slide/1|accessdate=October 22, 2016|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=October 19, 2016|author=CS|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022140910/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/777749-imax-and-warner-bros-extend-deal-to-include-12-more-films#/slide/1|archivedate=October 22, 2016}}</ref> It also received an [[4DX]] release in selected countries.<ref name=\"4D\"/>\n\nOutside the US, the film was released in most territories between March 8\u201316, 2018, in Japan on March 21, 2018, and in Poland on April 6, 2018.\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Tomb Raider'' was released on digital streaming platforms on May 29, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|title=Tomb Raider DVD Release Date June 12, 2018|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=May 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012622/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|archivedate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> A 4K UHD Blu-Ray, Blu-ray and DVD release occurred on June 12, 2018. It was released in Australia on June 18, 2018 for Blu-ray, Ultra HD Blu-ray, Blu-ray 3D and DVD. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|title=Tomb Raider DVD Release Date June 12, 2018|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=May 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012622/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|archivedate=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Tomb Raider'' grossed $58.3 million in the United States and Canada, and $216.4 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $275 million according to MGM<ref>{{cite web |author=MGM PR |title=Michael De Luca to Replace Jonathan Glickman at MGM |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/jonathan-glickman-mgm-bond-michael-de-luca-1203456176/ |website=Variety |publisher=Variety |accessdate=4 January 2020|date=2020-01-03 }}</ref>, against a production budget in the range of $90\u2013106 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dcfilm0318.htm|title=''Tomb Raider'' (2018)|website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=December 27, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180623151114/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dcfilm0318.htm|archive-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"opening\" /> In order to [[break even]], estimations say the film needed to gross at least $275 million worldwide.<ref name=opening2/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Tomb Raider'' was released alongside ''[[Love, Simon]]'' and ''[[I Can Only Imagine (film)|I Can Only Imagine]]'', and was projected to gross $23\u201329 million from 3,854 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/will-tomb-raider-movie-finally-knock-black-panther-box-office-perch/|title=Will 'Tomb Raider' Be the Movie to Finally Knock 'Black Panther' From Box Office Perch?|author=Jeremy Fuster|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314051450/https://www.thewrap.com/will-tomb-raider-movie-finally-knock-black-panther-box-office-perch/|archivedate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The film made $9.1 million on its first day (including $2.1 million from Thursday night previews).<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-love-simon-box-office-weekend-1202339172/|title='Black Panther' Poised For $460M+ Profit; Faith-Based 'I Can Only Imagine' Surprises With $15M+|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 17, 2018|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 27, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6y38TtFM9?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-love-simon-box-office-weekend-1202339172/|archivedate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> It went on to open to $23.5 million, finishing second at the box office, behind ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' ($27 million in its fifth week).<ref name=opening2>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-i-can-only-imagine-love-simon-weekend-box-office-results-sunday-1202341517/|title='Black Panther' Keeps B.O. Treasure From 'Tomb Raider'; How 'I Can Only Imagine' Hit A $17M High Note|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 18, 2018|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6y38PDcrh?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-i-can-only-imagine-love-simon-weekend-box-office-results-sunday-1202341517/|archivedate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> It fell 55% to $10.6 million in its second weekend, finishing 5th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/pacific-rim-uprising-black-panther-weekend-box-office-1202352184/|title=Does 'Pacific Rim: Uprising' Break Even At The Global B.O.?; 'Black Panther' Sets Marvel Record \u2013 Sunday Postmortem|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 25, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324011649/http://deadline.com/2018/03/pacific-rim-uprising-black-panther-weekend-box-office-1202352184/|archivedate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> It grossed $4.9 million in its third weekend, falling 51% and finishing seventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/ready-player-one-steven-spielberg-opening-weekend-box-office-1202318581/|title=How Warner Bros. Sold 'Ready Player One' On The Spielberg Spirit & Beat Tracking With $53M+ 4-Day \u2013 Sunday Postmortem|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 1, 2018|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|accessdate=April 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401052441/http://deadline.com/2018/03/ready-player-one-steven-spielberg-opening-weekend-box-office-1202318581/|archivedate=April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, the film opened in nine Asian countries a week prior to its United States debut. It made $14.2 million over the weekend, with Korea's $2.9 million being the biggest market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-panther-china-tomb-raider-wrinkle-in-time-international-box-office-weekend-results-1202334223/ |title='Black Panther' Tops $500M Overseas, $1B WW With $67M China Bow; 'Tomb Raider' Kicks Off \u2013 International Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=March 11, 2018 |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xrsq1S9R?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-panther-china-tomb-raider-wrinkle-in-time-international-box-office-weekend-results-1202334223/ |archivedate=March 12, 2018 }}</ref> The film opened in China on March 16, 2018, and made $12.3 million the first day. It was the fifth-highest-grossing day for a Warner Bros. film, opening 6% higher than ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'', and went on to debut to $41 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title='Tomb Raider' Opens with $12.3 Million on first day in China|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/box-office-tomb-raider-china-1202728879/|date=March 16, 2018|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402230121/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/box-office-tomb-raider-china-1202728879/|archivedate=April 2, 2018}}</ref> {{asof|2018|04|28|df=US}}, the film's largest markets were China ($78.4 million), the United Kingdom ($10.4 million), France ($10.1 million), and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS countries]] ($7.5 million).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=dcfilm0318.htm|title=Tomb Raider (2018) - International Box Office Results|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001031153/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl|archivedate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 52% based on 305 reviews, and an average rating of 5.46/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Tomb Raider'' reboots the franchise with a more grounded approach and a star who's clearly more than up to the task\u2014neither of which are well served by an uninspired origin story.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tomb Raider (2018) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tomb_raider_2018|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> <!-- It is currently the best-reviewed [[Video game movie|movie based on a video game]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name=VGM>{{cite web|title=46 Video Game Movies Ranked by Tomatometer|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/video-game-movies-ranked-worst-to-best/|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 30, 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430174930/https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/video-game-movies-ranked-worst-to-best/|archivedate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> --> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 48 out of 100, based on 53 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/tomb-raider|title=Tomb Raider Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323222152/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/tomb-raider|archivedate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, the same score earned by the 2001 film; [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 70% positive score.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and said, \"The Lara Croft reboot ''Tomb Raider'' isn\u2019t half bad for an hour. Then there\u2019s another hour. That hour is quite bad. It\u2019s no fun watching your action heroine get shoved, punched and kicked to the sidelines of her own movie, while the menfolk take over and take turns overacting before expiring.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phillips |first1=Michael |author-link=Michael Phillips (critic) |title='Tomb Raider' review: Alicia Vikander is a craftier Croft but vanishes in second half of movie |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-tomb-raider-review-0314-story.html |accessdate=March 14, 2018 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=March 14, 2018 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180130/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-tomb-raider-review-0314-story.html |archive-date=March 14, 2018 |quote= turns Lara into a punching bag and an onlooker. }}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a mixed review, criticizing the story but praising Vikander, and writing, \"When all the one-dimensional supporting characters and familiar action moves fall by the wayside, the one thing left standing is Vikander...The film strains credulity even for a vid-game fantasy by letting the leading lady recover awfully quickly from bad injuries, but other than that Vikander commands attention and is the element here that makes ''Tomb Raider'' sort of watchable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= 'Tomb Raider': Film Review |author-link= Todd McCarthy |first= Todd |last= McCarthy |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=March 14, 2018 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/tomb-raider-review-1094069 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315033843/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/tomb-raider-review-1094069|archivedate=March 15, 2018 |quote= a grimly determined by-the-numbers rehash of the same sort of plots and action moves that animated the first two Lara Croft films |accessdate= October 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOwen Gleiberman of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film, saying that \"The exciting surprise of the new ''Tomb Raider'', directed by the Norwegian genre specialist Roar Uthaug, is that it doesn\u2019t tamp down Vikander\u2019s inner flame, or the three-dimensionality of her talent; it doesn\u2019t fold and insert her into an overly gymnastic and CGI-happy thrill ride. The movie is full of vine-swinging, bow-and-arrow-shooting, ancient-spirit-meeting action, but most of it is staged on a convincing human scale, one that\u2019s been expertly tailored to its star\u2019s understated directness.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= March 14, 2018 |last1= Gleiberman |first1= Owen |author-link= Owen Gleiberman |title= Film Review: 'Tomb Raider' |url= https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/tomb-raider-review-alicia-vikander-1202722123/ |website= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= [[Penske Business Media]] |accessdate= April 6, 2018 |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180407115830/https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/tomb-raider-review-alicia-vikander-1202722123/ |archive-date= April 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nMatt Zoller Seitz of [[Roger Ebert|RogerEbert.com]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, and said, \"this is a beautifully crafted and unpretentious piece of action cinema, with a number of sequences that are as gorgeous as they are thrilling, and a female hero who's as elegant as she is deadly: an ass-kicking [[Audrey Hepburn]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zoller Seitz|first1=Matt|title=Tomb Raider Movie Review and Summary|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tomb-raider-2018|website=RogerEbert.com|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|accessdate=April 6, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094022/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tomb-raider-2018|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRetrospectively, some critics have argued that ''Tomb Raider'' was overly scrutinised by press compared to similar films in the same genre.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kain |first1=Erik |title=The Critics Must Be Crazy: 'Tomb Raider' Is A Great Video Game Movie |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/05/17/tomb-raider-was-a-pretty-great-video-game-movie/#21da8f38756d |website=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mutlu |first1=Busra |title=Here's exactly why the Tomb Raider film didn't deserve any of its bad press |url=https://thetempest.co/2018/06/14/entertainment/tomb-raider-reboot-film/ |website=The Tempest|date=2018-06-14 }}</ref> Editor in Large of IndieWire [[Anne_Thompson_(film_critic) | Anne Thompson]] theorised that it wasn't marketed enough to smart women.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |title=I'm with you. My humble theory: it plays best for a niche it did not market to smart women. |url=https://twitter.com/akstanwyck/status/975901788254564352 |website=Twitter}}</ref> Thompson also wrote that Tomb Raider \"was a well-mounted, intelligently wrought adventure, more grounded in the real world than its fantasy predecessors\" and that \"it establishes the action bonafides of both Vikander and director Roar Uthaug\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |title='Tomb Raider' Isn't a Hit, but Alicia Vikander and Her Director Come Out Ahead |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-alicia-vikander-tweener-box-office-1201942444/ |website=IndieWire |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614171603/http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-alicia-vikander-tweener-box-office-1201942444/ |archivedate=2018-06-14 |date=2018-03-26 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2018 Teen Choice Awards|August 12, 2018]]\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie \u2013 Action|Choice Movie \u2013 Action]]\n| ''Tomb Raider''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglas|first1=Esme|title=Teen Choice Awards 2018: See the full list of winners|url=https://ew.com/awards/2018/08/12/teen-choice-awards-winners-list/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW]]|accessdate=August 13, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813151232/https://ew.com/awards/2018/08/12/teen-choice-awards-winners-list/|archivedate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Action Movie - Actress\n| [[Alicia Vikander]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Future ==\nIn 2015, Adrian Askarieh, producer of the ''[[Hitman (franchise)#Films|Hitman]]'' films, stated that he hoped to oversee a [[shared universe]] of [[Square Enix]] films with ''[[Just Cause (video game series)#Film|Just Cause]]'', ''Hitman'', ''Tomb Raider'', ''[[Deus Ex (series)#Related media|Deus Ex]]'', and ''[[Thief (series)#Film|Thief]]'', but admitted that he does not have the rights to ''Tomb Raider''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/09/hitman-producer-dreams-of-shared-square-enix-movie-universe|title=Hitman producer dreams of shared Square Enix movie universe|work=[[IGN]]|last=Krupa|first=Daniel|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720151342/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/09/hitman-producer-dreams-of-shared-square-enix-movie-universe|archivedate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the release of the first film, Alicia Vikander expressed interest in returning as Lara Croft for a second film, stating that \"If there's an audience out there for it, then I would love to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a850813/alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-sequel-would-love/|title=Alicia Vikander reveals she \"would love\" to do a Tomb Raider sequel|date=February 24, 2018|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref> In April 2019, Amy Jump was hired to write a script for a possible sequel, with Vikander attached.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/tomb-raider-sequel-mgm-warner-bros-amy-jump-write-script-1202594616/|title=MGM & Warner Bros Starts Climb Toward 'Tomb Raider 2,' Amy Jump To Write Script|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 12, 2019|first1=Mike|last1=Fleming Jr|accessdate=April 13, 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, [[Ben Wheatley]], Jump's husband, signed on to direct the sequel, with a planned March 19, 2021 release date, with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] dropping out of the project. That same month, it was confirmed that Wheatley's long-time cinematographer Laurie Rose will also work on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/tomb-raider-sequel-ben-wheatley-director-alicia-vikander-lara-croft-mgm-march-19-2021-release-1202710550/|title=Ben Wheatley Set To Direct Alicia Vikander In 'Tomb Raider' Sequel; MGM Sets Release Date|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=September 4, 2019|first1=Mike|last1=Fleming Jr|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hnentertainment.co/free-fire-overlord-cinematographer-laurie-rose-expected-to-work-on-tomb-raider-2/|title='Free Fire/Overlord' Cinematographer Laurie Rose Expected To Work On 'Tomb Raider 2'|last=Marc|first=Christopher|work=HNEntertainment|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> It was announced that filming will start in early 2020 in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hnentertainment.co/ben-wheatleys-tomb-raider-2-starring-alicia-vikander-returning-to-england-to-shoot/|title=Ben Wheatley's 'Tomb Raider 2' Starring Alicia Vikander Returning To England To Shoot|last=Marc|first=Christopher|work=HNEntertainment|date=November 1, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> According to Geek Vibes Nation, principal photography was scheduled to start in April with filming taking place across a number of countries including England, South Africa, Finland and China and looking to deliver a faithful adaptation of the games' story, the movies will allegedly be embracing more of the supernatural elements and tones that gamers have connected with. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://geekvibesnation.com/new-tomb-raider-sequel-details-revealed/|title=New Tomb Raider Sequel Details Revealed|author=Cainan|work=Geek Vibes Nation|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> Production has now been delayed until sometime this Summer with filming now taking place in England and South Africa due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://geekvibesnation.com/tomb-raider-moves-production-date-to-summer/|title=Tomb Raider Sequel Moves Production Date To Summer|author=Cainan|work=Geek Vibes Nation|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tombraidermovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1365519}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|tomb_raider_2018|Tomb Raider}}\n\n{{Tomb Raider series}}\n{{Films directed by Roar Uthaug}}\n\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 3D films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:4D films]]\n[[Category:British action adventure films]]\n[[Category:British coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roar Uthaug]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Junkie XL]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2018]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Films set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Films set on fictional islands]]\n[[Category:Films set on oceans]]\n[[Category:Films set on uninhabited islands]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Africa]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Live-action films based on video games]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Reboot films]]\n[[Category:Tomb Raider films]]\n[[Category:Works based on Square Enix video games]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 film directed by Roar Uthaug}}\n{{about|the 2018 film starring Alicia Vikander|the 2001 film starring Angelina Jolie|Lara Croft: Tomb Raider}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Tomb Raider\n| image          = Tomb Raider (2018 film).png\n| alt            = A close-up shot of a gritty-looking Lara Croft is seen with the film's title, her actress' name and company logos on the bottom.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roar Uthaug]]\n| producer       = [[Graham King]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Geneva Robertson-Dworet]]\n* Alastair Siddons\n}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Evan Daugherty\n* Geneva Robertson-Dworet\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Tomb Raider (2013 video game)|Tomb Raider]]''|[[Crystal Dynamics]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Alicia Vikander]]\n* [[Dominic West]]\n* [[Walton Goggins]]\n* [[Daniel Wu]]\n* [[Kristin Scott Thomas]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Junkie XL|Tom Holkenborg]]\n| cinematography = [[George Richmond (cinematographer)|George Richmond]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Stuart Baird]]\n* [[Michael Tronick]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]<ref name=\"insight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php|title=Film Releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315044131/https://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php|work=[[Variety Insight]]|publisher=Variety Media|accessdate=March 15, 2018|archivedate=March 15, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]<ref name=\"insight\" /> \n* [[GK Films]]<ref name=\"insight\" />\n* [[Square Enix]]<ref name=\"insight\" />\n}}\n| distributor    = Warner Bros. Pictures<ref name=\"insight\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|3|2|[[Berlin]]|ref1=<ref name=\"prem1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dvd-forum.at/news-details/69347-events-tomb-raider-das-war-die-exklusive-preview-mit-alicia-vikander |title=\"Tomb Raider\": Das war die exklusive Preview mit Alicia Vikander|date=March 3, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018|work=DVD-Forum.at |first=Daniel |last=Fabian |language=de}}</ref><ref name=\"prem2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylbLMuhrkW0|title=TOMB RAIDER - Premierenclip Deutsch HD German (2018)|work=Warner Bros. DE|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=March 5, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094038/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ylbLMuhrkW0|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>|2018|3|14|United Kingdom|2018|3|16|United States}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/tomb-raider-film | title=TOMB RAIDER (12A) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=February 23, 2018 | accessdate=March 8, 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309182707/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/tomb-raider-film | archivedate=March 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* United Kingdom<ref name=BFI>{{cite web|title=Tomb Raider (2018)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5aa1d2662fc38|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316030150/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5aa1d2662fc38|archive-date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* United States<ref name=BFI/>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $90\u2013106 million<ref name=\"opening\" />\n| gross          = $275 million<ref>{{cite web |author=MGM PR |title=Michael De Luca to Replace Jonathan Glickman at MGM |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/jonathan-glickman-mgm-bond-michael-de-luca-1203456176/ |website=Variety |publisher=Variety |accessdate=4 January 2020|date=2020-01-03 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Tomb Raider''''' is a 2018 [[Action film|action]] [[adventure film]] directed by [[Roar Uthaug]], with a screenplay by [[Geneva Robertson-Dworet]] and Alastair Siddons, from a story by [[Evan Daugherty]] and Robertson-Dworet. An [[United States|American]] and [[United Kingdom|British]] co-production, it is based on the [[Tomb Raider (2013 video game)|2013 video game of the same name]], with some elements of [[Rise of the Tomb Raider|its sequel]] by [[Crystal Dynamics]], and is a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of the ''[[Tomb Raider]]'' film series. The film stars [[Alicia Vikander]] as [[Lara Croft]], who embarks on a perilous journey to her father's last-known destination, hoping to solve the mystery of his disappearance. [[Dominic West]], [[Walton Goggins]], [[Daniel Wu]], and [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] appear in supporting roles.\n\n[[Principal photography]] lasted from January to June 2017, and took place at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, and in [[Cape Town]], South Africa. The first ''Tomb Raider'' film not to be distributed by [[Paramount Pictures]], it was released in the United Kingdom on March 14, 2018, and in the United States on March 16, 2018, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], in [[RealD 3D]], [[IMAX|IMAX 3D]], [[IMAX]] and [[4DX]].<ref name=\"4D\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kitag.com/en/movies/tomb-raider-4dx/|title='Tomb Raider' - 4DX|work=Kitag|date=March 1, 2018|accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> The film grossed over $275 million worldwide, outperforming both the 2001 film [[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider|of the same name]] and its 2003 [[Lara Croft: Tomb Raider \u2013 The Cradle of Life|sequel]].\n\n''Tomb Raider'' received mixed reviews from critics, with some describing the plot as paint \"by-the-numbers\", and others praising the action sequences, tone, grittiness and realistic take on the franchise. Vikander's performance and the characterization of Croft drew a polarized response; some described her as a \"capable, powerful, and unobjectified heroine\", while others called her bland, and a \"punching bag and onlooker.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=March 14, 2018 |title= 'Tomb Raider': What the Critics Are Saying |first= Katie |last= Kilkenny |work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher= [[Prometheus Global Media]] |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-review-roundup-1094464 |accessdate= October 24, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180314224426/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-review-roundup-1094464 |archive-date= March 14, 2018 }}</ref> A sequel is scheduled to be released in March 2021.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- As per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nFollowing the disappearance of her father, Lord Richard Croft, [[Lara Croft]] makes a living as a [[bike courier]]. When she is arrested after a bike accident involving a police car, Richard's business partner Ana Miller posts her bail. Lara has never claimed her inheritance for many years as she believes her father to still be alive, but Miller warns Lara that if she does not claim it, her father's country estate, Croft Manor, will be sold off. Lara reluctantly accepts and gains access to a secret chamber in her father's tomb. There she finds a pre-recorded video message from Richard detailing his research into [[Himiko]], the mythical Queen of [[Yamatai]] who was said to command the power over life and death. Richard warns Lara to destroy all of his research, but she ignores his warnings so that she can investigate further.\n\nLara travels to [[Hong Kong]] where she hires Lu Ren, captain of the ship ''Endurance'', to sail into the [[Devil's Sea]] and the island of Yamatai. The ship capsizes in a violent storm and Lara is washed ashore where she is knocked unconscious. She awakens only to encounter Mathias Vogel, the leader of an expedition to locate Himiko's tomb. The expedition has been funded by a shadowy organization called Trinity, which seeks to harness and weaponize Himiko's power. Vogel takes Lara prisoner, claiming that he killed her father and revealing that he intends to use Richard's research to continue his expedition. He adds Lara and Lu Ren to his slave force; eventually, the two of them try to escape, and Lara is the only one successful.\n\nAfter surviving rapids and narrowly avoiding going over a waterfall with the wreck of a wartime airplane, Lara is forced to kill a Trinity guard after nightfall. She follows a mysterious figure through the jungle, and discovers that the figure is her father, who stayed on the island to prevent Trinity from finding Himiko's tomb. After Lara convinces him that she is real and not a figment of his imagination, Richard treats her injuries. Despite his protests, Lara sets off the next morning to steal Vogel's satellite phone. Lara makes contact with Lu Ren, and he, along with the other slaves, stage a distraction that allows Lara to infiltrate the Trinity camp and take the phone. In the ensuing chaos, Lu Ren commandeers an assault rifle, provides cover for the escapees and guns down several Trinity soldiers, while Richard makes his way to Himiko's tomb and is captured by Vogel, who persuades Lara to open the tomb, something she has prepared for since she was a child. At that point, the entrance to the tomb self-destructs and falls away, thus enabling the party to enter that which has not been seen for at least two thousand years.\n\nThe party navigates a series of booby traps and locates Himiko's [[sarcophagus]]. When a Trinity soldier attempts to remove her corpse, he is infected by a highly infectious pathogen that reduces those infected to an aggressive zombie-like state. Lara realizes that Himiko was an asymptomatic carrier of the virus, who chose to entomb herself so that she could not infect others. Vogel concludes that he cannot remove Himiko's body and instead settles for detaching a finger, which he seals in a pouch. In the confusion, Lara and Richard overpower the remaining soldiers, although Vogel escapes and Richard becomes infected. Knowing there is no cure, Richard proposes destroying Himiko's tomb to prevent the disease from spreading across the world. Lara pursues Vogel as Richard sets off a bomb, killing himself and sealing the tomb. Lara confronts and kills Vogel by infecting him with the finger. She escapes the tomb as it collapses, regrouping with Lu Ren and the slaves; they commandeer a Trinity helicopter to escape Yamatai.\n\nLara returns to London, where she formally accepts her inheritance and inadvertently discovers that Trinity's [[front company]], Patna, is actually a [[subsidiary]] of Croft Holdings. She proceeds to investigate Trinity further and begins to suspect that Ana is one of their agents who manipulated her into accepting her inheritance; this was to have Lara sign over control of Croft Holdings' business operations to her when Richard stopped cooperating with Trinity. Having witnessed Trinity's ruthlessness firsthand, she prepares for her next adventure.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], Lara returns to Alan's pawn shop to buy weapons and decides to take two identical pistols.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Alicia Vikander]] as [[Lara Croft]]\n** Maisy De Freitas as 7-year-old Lara\n** [[Emily Carey]] as 14-year-old Lara\n* [[Dominic West]] as Lord Richard Croft, Lara's archaeologist father.\n* [[Walton Goggins]] as Mathias Vogel, a rival archaeologist of Richard Croft, and a member of Trinity, a shadowy organization.\n* [[Daniel Wu]] as Lu Ren, the ship captain who helps Lara to search for her father.\n* [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] as Ana Miller, an associate at Richard Croft's company, Croft Holdings.\n* [[Derek Jacobi]] as Mr. Yaffe, an associate at Croft Holdings.\n* [[Nick Frost]] as Alan, a pawn shop owner.\n* [[Jaime Winstone]] as Pamela, Alan's wife\n* [[Hannah John-Kamen]] as Sophie, Lara's friend\n\nAdditionally, [[Antonio Aakeel]] play Lara's friend Nitin. [[Duncan Airlie James]] plays Terry, a mixed martial arts club operator. [[Josef Altin]] portrays Lara's boss Bruce, Billy Postlethwaite and [[Roger Nsengiyumva]] appear as Bill and Rog, Lara's co-workers and opponents at the race, and [[Michael Obiora]] portrays Baxter, the Croft Holdings' receptionist.\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[GK Films]] first acquired the rights to make the film in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/news/the-departed-the-town-producer-plans-tomb-raider-reboot-for-2013/|title='The Departed' & 'The Town' Producer Plans 'Tomb Raider' Reboot For 2013|publisher=The Film Stage|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094035/https://thefilmstage.com/news/the-departed-the-town-producer-plans-tomb-raider-reboot-for-2013/|archivedate=2018-03-18|date=2011-03-08}}</ref> Norwegian director [[Roar Uthaug]] came on board in November 2015,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Finds Director (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-reboot-finds-director-840824|accessdate=March 6, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=November 17, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310162405/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/tomb-raider-reboot-finds-director-840824|archivedate=March 10, 2016}}</ref> and [[Alicia Vikander]] was cast as the new Lara Croft in April 2016.<ref name=\"VikanderCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Alicia Vikander to Star as Lara Croft in 'Tomb Raider'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alicia-vikander-star-as-lara-888593|accessdate=April 29, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=April 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828131755/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/alicia-vikander-star-as-lara-888593|archivedate=August 28, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' had previously reported that [[Daisy Ridley]] was considered for the role,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaafar|first1=Ali|title=Is 'Star Wars' Daisy Ridley Being Eyed As Lara Croft In 'Tomb Raider' Reboot?|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/daisy-ridley-lara-croft-tomb-raider-star-wars-force-awakens-1201717660/|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311114719/http://deadline.com/2016/03/daisy-ridley-lara-croft-tomb-raider-star-wars-force-awakens-1201717660/|archivedate=March 11, 2016}}</ref> though Ridley later stated in an interview that it was just \"the craziest rumor [she had] ever heard about [herself]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doUdRCrK80E|title=73 Questions With Daisy Ridley|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=January 20, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120134408/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doUdRCrK80E|archivedate=January 20, 2018}}</ref> [[Walton Goggins]] was announced to play the villain in December 2016,<ref name=\"GogginsCast\">{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Casts Walton Goggins as Villain Opposite Alicia Vikander (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-casts-walton-goggins-villain-alicia-vikander-1201886922/|accessdate=December 8, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=December 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209202819/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-casts-walton-goggins-villain-alicia-vikander-1201886922/|archivedate=December 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheridan|first1=Connor|title=Tomb Raider reboot movie is like Raiders of the Lost Ark according to bad guy actor Walton Goggins|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/tomb-raider-reboot-movie-is-like-raiders-of-the-lost-ark-according-to-bad-guy-actor-walton-goggins/|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|publisher=Future Publishing|accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217110901/http://www.gamesradar.com/tomb-raider-reboot-movie-is-like-raiders-of-the-lost-ark-according-to-bad-guy-actor-walton-goggins/|archivedate=December 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/tomb-raider-movie-walton-goggins-villain/|title='Tomb Raider': Walton Goggins on His \"Confused\", \"Angry\", and \"Desperate\" Villain|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|publisher=Future Media|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|date=December 27, 2016|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094033/http://collider.com/tomb-raider-movie-walton-goggins-villain/|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref> and much of the rest of the cast was revealed in early 2017.<ref name=WuCast>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/tomb-raider-reboot-daniel-wu-1201958245/|title='Tomb Raider' Reboot Adds 'Into the Badlands' Star Daniel Wu (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=January 11, 2017|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094033/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/tomb-raider-reboot-daniel-wu-1201958245/|archivedate=March 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestCast\">{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Dominic West Joins Alicia Vikander in 'Tomb Raider' (Exclusive)|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dominic-west-joins-alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-943069|accessdate=January 30, 2017|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=January 27, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129194420/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/dominic-west-joins-alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-943069|archivedate=January 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Busch|first1=Anita|title=Hannah John-Kamen Joins 'Tomb Raider' Cast; Andre Royo Steps Into Amazon's 'Beautiful Boy'|url=http://deadline.com/2017/04/hannah-john-kamen-tomb-raider-andre-royo-beauitful-boy-1202069567/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 13, 2017|accessdate=April 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on January 23, 2017, in [[Cape Town]], South Africa, and wrapped on June 9, 2017, at [[Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England.<ref name=\"Jan2017CS\">{{cite news|last1=Perry|first1=Spencer|title=New Tomb Raider Movie Filming Has Begun!|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/806047-production-officially-begins-on-the-new-tomb-raider-movie|accessdate=January 24, 2017|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=January 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125175132/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/806047-production-officially-begins-on-the-new-tomb-raider-movie|archivedate=January 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/tomb-raider-remake-production-start-date-2017/|title=Tomb Raider Reboot Begins Shooting in January 2017|date=December 22, 2016|accessdate=December 23, 2016|last=Scott|first=Ryan|work=[[MovieWeb]]|publisher=Watchr Media|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223034022/http://movieweb.com/tomb-raider-remake-production-start-date-2017/|archivedate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/tomb-raider-movie-head-production/|title=Tomb Raider Movie Is About To Head Into Production|date=December 22, 2016|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=We Got This Covered|last=Myles|first=Sarah|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223172433/http://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/tomb-raider-movie-head-production/|archivedate=December 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lesnick|first1=Silas|title=New Tomb Raider Movie Wraps Production|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/857033-new-tomb-raider-movie#/slide/1|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609194930/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/857033-new-tomb-raider-movie#/slide/1|archivedate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Wilton House]] near [[Salisbury]] in [[Wiltshire]] was the location for exterior shots for Croft Manor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1365519/locations?ref_=tt_ql_dt_5#filming_locations |title=Tomb Raider (2018): Filming & Production |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=April 6, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307191317/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1365519/locations?ref_=tt_ql_dt_5#filming_locations |archivedate=March 7, 2018 }}</ref> The waterfall sequence involving the plane was filmed at a waterpark at Lee Valley, outside of London, at a venue that had been built for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], and was combined with footage filmed in South Africa.<ref name=\"VFXVoice\">{{cite news|last1=Failes|first1=Ian|title=TOMB RAIDER: Transforming the Waterfall Scene with Frame-By-Frame VFX|url=http://vfxvoice.com/tomb-raider-transforming-the-waterfall-scene-with-frame-by-frame-vfx/|accessdate=April 10, 2018|work=VFX Voice|date=April 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411032905/http://vfxvoice.com/tomb-raider-transforming-the-waterfall-scene-with-frame-by-frame-vfx/|archivedate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main article|Tomb Raider (soundtrack)}}\nOn June 14, 2017, It was announced that [[Junkie XL]] signed on as the film's composer after being removed from ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Burlingame |first1=Russ |title=Junkie XL Issues Statement on Being \"Replaced\" On Justice League |url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2017/06/15/junkie-xl-issues-statement-on-being-replaced-on-justice-league/ |website=Comic Book |accessdate=August 27, 2018}}</ref> The soundtrack was released digitally on March 9, 2018 by [[Sony Classical Records]], with the physical edition being released on March 16, 2018, followed by the vinyl on August 24, 2018.\n\n===Visual effects===\nThe visual effects are provided by [[Scanline VFX]] and Supervised by Nick Crew and Paul Linden with the help of [[Method Studios]], [[Rising Sun Pictures]], Mr. X, Soho VFX, [[ZERO VFX|Zero VFX]] and Factory VFX.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=January 1, 2019|title=TOMB RAIDER -The Art of VFXThe Art of VFX|url=https://www.artofvfx.com/tomb-raider/|website=www.artofvfx.com|date=2018-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Tomb Raider'' premiered on March 2, 2018, in [[Berlin]], Germany, at an exclusive preview with invited guests and [[cosplay]]ing fans.<ref name=\"prem1\" /><ref name=\"prem2\" /> It was released in the United States on March 16, 2018, by [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Alicia Vikander's 'Tomb Raider' Gets 2018 Release Date|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-release-date-alicia-vikander-1201810114/|accessdate=July 10, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=July 7, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710042013/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/tomb-raider-release-date-alicia-vikander-1201810114/|archivedate=July 10, 2016}}</ref>. The film received an [[IMAX 3D]] and a [[RealD 3D]] release.<ref>{{cite news|title=IMAX and Warner Bros. Extend Deal to Include 12 More Films|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/777749-imax-and-warner-bros-extend-deal-to-include-12-more-films#/slide/1|accessdate=October 22, 2016|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline Media]]|date=October 19, 2016|author=CS|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022140910/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/777749-imax-and-warner-bros-extend-deal-to-include-12-more-films#/slide/1|archivedate=October 22, 2016}}</ref> It also received an [[4DX]] release in selected countries.<ref name=\"4D\"/>\n\nOutside the US, the film was released in most territories between March 8\u201316, 2018, in Japan on March 21, 2018, and in Poland on April 6, 2018.\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Tomb Raider'' was released on digital streaming platforms on May 29, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|title=Tomb Raider DVD Release Date June 12, 2018|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=May 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012622/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|archivedate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> A 4K UHD Blu-Ray, Blu-ray and DVD release occurred on June 12, 2018. It was released in Australia on June 18, 2018 for Blu-ray, Ultra HD Blu-ray, Blu-ray 3D and DVD. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|title=Tomb Raider DVD Release Date June 12, 2018|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=May 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012622/https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/6277/Tomb-Raider-2018.html|archivedate=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Tomb Raider'' grossed $58.3 million in the United States and Canada, and $216.4 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $275 million according to MGM<ref>{{cite web |author=MGM PR |title=Michael De Luca to Replace Jonathan Glickman at MGM |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/jonathan-glickman-mgm-bond-michael-de-luca-1203456176/ |website=Variety |publisher=Variety |accessdate=4 January 2020|date=2020-01-03 }}</ref>, against a production budget in the range of $90\u2013106 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dcfilm0318.htm|title=''Tomb Raider'' (2018)|website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=December 27, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180623151114/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dcfilm0318.htm|archive-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"opening\" /> In order to [[break even]], estimations say the film needed to gross at least $275 million worldwide.<ref name=opening2/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Tomb Raider'' was released alongside ''[[Love, Simon]]'' and ''[[I Can Only Imagine (film)|I Can Only Imagine]]'', and was projected to gross $23\u201329 million from 3,854 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=preview>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/will-tomb-raider-movie-finally-knock-black-panther-box-office-perch/|title=Will 'Tomb Raider' Be the Movie to Finally Knock 'Black Panther' From Box Office Perch?|author=Jeremy Fuster|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=March 13, 2018|accessdate=March 13, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314051450/https://www.thewrap.com/will-tomb-raider-movie-finally-knock-black-panther-box-office-perch/|archivedate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> The film made $9.1 million on its first day (including $2.1 million from Thursday night previews).<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-love-simon-box-office-weekend-1202339172/|title='Black Panther' Poised For $460M+ Profit; Faith-Based 'I Can Only Imagine' Surprises With $15M+|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 17, 2018|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 27, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6y38TtFM9?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-love-simon-box-office-weekend-1202339172/|archivedate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> It went on to open to $23.5 million, finishing second at the box office, behind ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' ($27 million in its fifth week).<ref name=opening2>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-i-can-only-imagine-love-simon-weekend-box-office-results-sunday-1202341517/|title='Black Panther' Keeps B.O. Treasure From 'Tomb Raider'; How 'I Can Only Imagine' Hit A $17M High Note|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 18, 2018|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 18, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6y38PDcrh?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-black-panther-i-can-only-imagine-love-simon-weekend-box-office-results-sunday-1202341517/|archivedate=March 20, 2018}}</ref> It fell 55% to $10.6 million in its second weekend, finishing 5th at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/pacific-rim-uprising-black-panther-weekend-box-office-1202352184/|title=Does 'Pacific Rim: Uprising' Break Even At The Global B.O.?; 'Black Panther' Sets Marvel Record \u2013 Sunday Postmortem|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=March 25, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=March 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180324011649/http://deadline.com/2018/03/pacific-rim-uprising-black-panther-weekend-box-office-1202352184/|archivedate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> It grossed $4.9 million in its third weekend, falling 51% and finishing seventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/ready-player-one-steven-spielberg-opening-weekend-box-office-1202318581/|title=How Warner Bros. Sold 'Ready Player One' On The Spielberg Spirit & Beat Tracking With $53M+ 4-Day \u2013 Sunday Postmortem|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 1, 2018|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|accessdate=April 4, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401052441/http://deadline.com/2018/03/ready-player-one-steven-spielberg-opening-weekend-box-office-1202318581/|archivedate=April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, the film opened in nine Asian countries a week prior to its United States debut. It made $14.2 million over the weekend, with Korea's $2.9 million being the biggest market.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-panther-china-tomb-raider-wrinkle-in-time-international-box-office-weekend-results-1202334223/ |title='Black Panther' Tops $500M Overseas, $1B WW With $67M China Bow; 'Tomb Raider' Kicks Off \u2013 International Box Office |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |date=March 11, 2018 |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |accessdate=March 11, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xrsq1S9R?url=http://deadline.com/2018/03/black-panther-china-tomb-raider-wrinkle-in-time-international-box-office-weekend-results-1202334223/ |archivedate=March 12, 2018 }}</ref> The film opened in China on March 16, 2018, and made $12.3 million the first day. It was the fifth-highest-grossing day for a Warner Bros. film, opening 6% higher than ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'', and went on to debut to $41 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title='Tomb Raider' Opens with $12.3 Million on first day in China|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/box-office-tomb-raider-china-1202728879/|date=March 16, 2018|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|accessdate=April 6, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180402230121/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/box-office-tomb-raider-china-1202728879/|archivedate=April 2, 2018}}</ref> {{asof|2018|04|28|df=US}}, the film's largest markets were China ($78.4 million), the United Kingdom ($10.4 million), France ($10.1 million), and the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS countries]] ($7.5 million).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=dcfilm0318.htm|title=Tomb Raider (2018) - International Box Office Results|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001031153/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl|archivedate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 52% based on 305 reviews, and an average rating of 5.46/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Tomb Raider'' reboots the franchise with a more grounded approach and a star who's clearly more than up to the task\u2014neither of which are well served by an uninspired origin story.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Tomb Raider (2018) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/tomb_raider_2018|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> <!-- It is currently the best-reviewed [[Video game movie|movie based on a video game]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name=VGM>{{cite web|title=46 Video Game Movies Ranked by Tomatometer|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/video-game-movies-ranked-worst-to-best/|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=April 30, 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430174930/https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/video-game-movies-ranked-worst-to-best/|archivedate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> --> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 48 out of 100, based on 53 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/tomb-raider|title=Tomb Raider Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323222152/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/tomb-raider|archivedate=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, the same score earned by the 2001 film; [[PostTrak]] reported filmgoers gave it a 70% positive score.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and said, \"The Lara Croft reboot ''Tomb Raider'' isn\u2019t half bad for an hour. Then there\u2019s another hour. That hour is quite bad. It\u2019s no fun watching your action heroine get shoved, punched and kicked to the sidelines of her own movie, while the menfolk take over and take turns overacting before expiring.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Phillips |first1=Michael |author-link=Michael Phillips (critic) |title='Tomb Raider' review: Alicia Vikander is a craftier Croft but vanishes in second half of movie |url= http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-tomb-raider-review-0314-story.html |accessdate=March 14, 2018 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=March 14, 2018 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180314180130/http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-tomb-raider-review-0314-story.html |archive-date=March 14, 2018 |quote= turns Lara into a punching bag and an onlooker. }}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a mixed review, criticizing the story but praising Vikander, and writing, \"When all the one-dimensional supporting characters and familiar action moves fall by the wayside, the one thing left standing is Vikander...The film strains credulity even for a vid-game fantasy by letting the leading lady recover awfully quickly from bad injuries, but other than that Vikander commands attention and is the element here that makes ''Tomb Raider'' sort of watchable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title= 'Tomb Raider': Film Review |author-link= Todd McCarthy |first= Todd |last= McCarthy |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=March 14, 2018 |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/tomb-raider-review-1094069 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315033843/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/tomb-raider-review-1094069|archivedate=March 15, 2018 |quote= a grimly determined by-the-numbers rehash of the same sort of plots and action moves that animated the first two Lara Croft films |accessdate= October 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOwen Gleiberman of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film, saying that \"The exciting surprise of the new ''Tomb Raider'', directed by the Norwegian genre specialist Roar Uthaug, is that it doesn\u2019t tamp down Vikander\u2019s inner flame, or the three-dimensionality of her talent; it doesn\u2019t fold and insert her into an overly gymnastic and CGI-happy thrill ride. The movie is full of vine-swinging, bow-and-arrow-shooting, ancient-spirit-meeting action, but most of it is staged on a convincing human scale, one that\u2019s been expertly tailored to its star\u2019s understated directness.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= March 14, 2018 |last1= Gleiberman |first1= Owen |author-link= Owen Gleiberman |title= Film Review: 'Tomb Raider' |url= https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/tomb-raider-review-alicia-vikander-1202722123/ |website= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= [[Penske Business Media]] |accessdate= April 6, 2018 |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180407115830/https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/tomb-raider-review-alicia-vikander-1202722123/ |archive-date= April 7, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nMatt Zoller Seitz of [[Roger Ebert|RogerEbert.com]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, and said, \"this is a beautifully crafted and unpretentious piece of action cinema, with a number of sequences that are as gorgeous as they are thrilling, and a female hero who's as elegant as she is deadly: an ass-kicking [[Audrey Hepburn]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zoller Seitz|first1=Matt|title=Tomb Raider Movie Review and Summary|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tomb-raider-2018|website=RogerEbert.com|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|accessdate=April 6, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318094022/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tomb-raider-2018|archive-date=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRetrospectively, some critics have argued that ''Tomb Raider'' was overly scrutinised by press compared to similar films in the same genre.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kain |first1=Erik |title=The Critics Must Be Crazy: 'Tomb Raider' Is A Great Video Game Movie |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/05/17/tomb-raider-was-a-pretty-great-video-game-movie/#21da8f38756d |website=Forbes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mutlu |first1=Busra |title=Here's exactly why the Tomb Raider film didn't deserve any of its bad press |url=https://thetempest.co/2018/06/14/entertainment/tomb-raider-reboot-film/ |website=The Tempest|date=2018-06-14 }}</ref> Editor in Large of IndieWire [[Anne_Thompson_(film_critic) | Anne Thompson]] theorised that it wasn't marketed enough to smart women.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |title=I'm with you. My humble theory: it plays best for a niche it did not market to smart women. |url=https://twitter.com/akstanwyck/status/975901788254564352 |website=Twitter}}</ref> Thompson also wrote that Tomb Raider \"was a well-mounted, intelligently wrought adventure, more grounded in the real world than its fantasy predecessors\" and that \"it establishes the action bonafides of both Vikander and director Roar Uthaug\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Anne |title='Tomb Raider' Isn't a Hit, but Alicia Vikander and Her Director Come Out Ahead |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-alicia-vikander-tweener-box-office-1201942444/ |website=IndieWire |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614171603/http://www.indiewire.com/2018/03/tomb-raider-alicia-vikander-tweener-box-office-1201942444/ |archivedate=2018-06-14 |date=2018-03-26 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[2018 Teen Choice Awards|August 12, 2018]]\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie \u2013 Action|Choice Movie \u2013 Action]]\n| ''Tomb Raider''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|last1=Douglas|first1=Esme|title=Teen Choice Awards 2018: See the full list of winners|url=https://ew.com/awards/2018/08/12/teen-choice-awards-winners-list/|website=[[Entertainment Weekly|EW]]|accessdate=August 13, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813151232/https://ew.com/awards/2018/08/12/teen-choice-awards-winners-list/|archivedate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| Choice Action Movie - Actress\n| [[Alicia Vikander]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Future ==\nIn 2015, Adrian Askarieh, producer of the ''[[Hitman (franchise)#Films|Hitman]]'' films, stated that he hoped to oversee a [[shared universe]] of [[Square Enix]] films with ''[[Just Cause (video game series)#Film|Just Cause]]'', ''Hitman'', ''Tomb Raider'', ''[[Deus Ex (series)#Related media|Deus Ex]]'', and ''[[Thief (series)#Film|Thief]]'', but admitted that he does not have the rights to ''Tomb Raider''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/09/hitman-producer-dreams-of-shared-square-enix-movie-universe|title=Hitman producer dreams of shared Square Enix movie universe|work=[[IGN]]|last=Krupa|first=Daniel|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720151342/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/09/09/hitman-producer-dreams-of-shared-square-enix-movie-universe|archivedate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the release of the first film, Alicia Vikander expressed interest in returning as Lara Croft for a second film, stating that \"If there's an audience out there for it, then I would love to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a850813/alicia-vikander-tomb-raider-sequel-would-love/|title=Alicia Vikander reveals she \"would love\" to do a Tomb Raider sequel|date=February 24, 2018|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref> In April 2019, Amy Jump was hired to write a script for a possible sequel, with Vikander attached.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/tomb-raider-sequel-mgm-warner-bros-amy-jump-write-script-1202594616/|title=MGM & Warner Bros Starts Climb Toward 'Tomb Raider 2,' Amy Jump To Write Script|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=April 12, 2019|first1=Mike|last1=Fleming Jr|accessdate=April 13, 2019}}</ref> In September 2019, [[Ben Wheatley]], Jump's husband, signed on to direct the sequel, with a planned March 19, 2021 release date, with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] dropping out of the project. That same month, it was confirmed that Wheatley's long-time cinematographer Laurie Rose will also work on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/tomb-raider-sequel-ben-wheatley-director-alicia-vikander-lara-croft-mgm-march-19-2021-release-1202710550/|title=Ben Wheatley Set To Direct Alicia Vikander In 'Tomb Raider' Sequel; MGM Sets Release Date|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Business Media]]|date=September 4, 2019|first1=Mike|last1=Fleming Jr|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hnentertainment.co/free-fire-overlord-cinematographer-laurie-rose-expected-to-work-on-tomb-raider-2/|title='Free Fire/Overlord' Cinematographer Laurie Rose Expected To Work On 'Tomb Raider 2'|last=Marc|first=Christopher|work=HNEntertainment|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 25, 2019}}</ref> It was announced that filming will start in early 2020 in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hnentertainment.co/ben-wheatleys-tomb-raider-2-starring-alicia-vikander-returning-to-england-to-shoot/|title=Ben Wheatley's 'Tomb Raider 2' Starring Alicia Vikander Returning To England To Shoot|last=Marc|first=Christopher|work=HNEntertainment|date=November 1, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref> According to Geek Vibes Nation, principal photography was scheduled to start in April with filming taking place across a number of countries including England, South Africa, Finland and China and looking to deliver a faithful adaptation of the games' story, the movies will allegedly be embracing more of the supernatural elements and tones that gamers have connected with. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://geekvibesnation.com/new-tomb-raider-sequel-details-revealed/|title=New Tomb Raider Sequel Details Revealed|author=Cainan|work=Geek Vibes Nation|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> Production has now been delayed until sometime this Summer with filming now taking place in England and South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://geekvibesnation.com/tomb-raider-moves-production-date-to-summer/|title=Tomb Raider Sequel Moves Production Date To Summer|author=Cainan|work=Geek Vibes Nation|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.tombraidermovie.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1365519}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|tomb_raider_2018|Tomb Raider}}\n\n{{Tomb Raider series}}\n{{Films directed by Roar Uthaug}}\n\n[[Category:2010s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 3D films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:4D films]]\n[[Category:British action adventure films]]\n[[Category:British coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category